Barnabas: Is wherever you're asleep.

30
00:17:12.650 --> 00:17:16.180
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, let's get started then.

31
00:17:17.119 --> 00:17:24.310
Parithosh Jayanthi: Barnabus, do you want to start us off with DevNet updates? How's Glamsterdam DevNet 5 going? What's… what are things looking like?

32
00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:32.240
Barnabas: Sure. So .NET5 is going quite poorly today. It went nicely yesterday.

33
00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:38.699
Barnabas: there was apparently a peering bug in Prysm, and Grandinee also had

34
00:17:39.110 --> 00:17:48.419
Barnabas: a fork choice bug. The fork choice bug was triggered by a malicious Lodestar client that Nico has built yesterday, or the day before that.

35
00:17:50.330 --> 00:18:04.630
Barnabas: As far as I know, the Grandine bug is still not fixed, and the Prysm bug might be fixed. It's untested as of now. Potuz just pushed a new commit, and I'm building a new image should be rolling out in a

36
00:18:05.290 --> 00:18:06.679
Barnabas: Probably half an hour from now.

37
00:18:11.550 --> 00:18:19.320
Barnabas: once the Prysm bug is fixed, we should be, going back to finalization, and

38
00:18:19.590 --> 00:18:24.770
Barnabas: Other than that, I think most of the other clients were quite stable.

39
00:18:29.580 --> 00:18:38.080
Parithosh Jayanthi: Potuz, do you want to expand on why… why you guys were sending invalid PTC attestations, or, like, what triggers it?

40
00:18:38.080 --> 00:18:53.979
Potuz: Oh, this was a great find by, by Ayton, and was corroborated by Nico and his bot. So the issue is quite nice, because we need to have a discussion anyways as to what to do with this. So the issue is that PTC attestation should be sent even

41
00:18:54.190 --> 00:19:10.329
Potuz: for if it's not on your… on your… on your branch. Like, if you're… you're a PTC attester, the block that comes is not your head, but the payload that you see for that block is timely, you should attest to that payload, or you… if it's not timely, you should attest that it wasn't timely.

42
00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:25.089
Potuz: The problem is that we were determining our duties with our head state, any other duty for the validator, so the head state is telling us, you are in the PTC committee, you need to send a PTC attestation.

43
00:19:25.230 --> 00:19:40.240
Potuz: And then we call the beacon to get a PTC attestation, and the beacon says, well, for this slot, I have seen this block with a timely payload, but this block is in a different shuffling, and in that branch, we were not in the PTC committee.

44
00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:54.969
Potuz: So, the validator was asking for duties on one shuffling, it was sending an attestation for a different shuffling, which we weren't in the committee, and then everyone, including ourselves, weren't, were not validating that PTC attestation.

45
00:19:55.540 --> 00:20:04.649
Potuz: We don't check things that we broadcast ourselves. We could have saved it by checking, but I think it's just better not to do this.

46
00:20:04.790 --> 00:20:08.290
Potuz: Anyways, what we should be moving into

47
00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:19.410
Potuz: is into trying to send, at the stage, PTC attestation for different branches on different shuffling. Even if it's not our head shuffling, it's just that we need to check that,

48
00:20:19.660 --> 00:20:37.449
Potuz: that, well, that, that we are in the committee in that shuffling. The fix that I sent now is the lazy fix. If we… if we see a block for the current slot, but we're not in the shuffling, then we don't even check if we need to send a PTC attestation, we just don't send anything.

49
00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:48.989
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, nice. So this was already happening, and this then triggered the peering bug, or what was the…

50
00:20:48.990 --> 00:20:57.909
Potuz: Well, this can only… this can only happen when, you have, a non-finalized situation and very long forks.

51
00:20:58.070 --> 00:21:11.129
Potuz: So we already had these very long forks because of fork choice issues on adjusters on different sides, and then on top of that, we… as soon as this starts happening, then we get isolated, and now we are… every single node of rhythm is on a different fork.

52
00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:20.790
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): It means that you… you saw, PTC votes coming from other… other clients.

53
00:21:21.260 --> 00:21:30.310
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): correctly voting for… for the forks? Or you were the only one attempting to do that and doing it wrongly?

54
00:21:31.230 --> 00:21:33.959
Potuz: I think we are the only ones that are doing this wrongly.

55
00:21:35.850 --> 00:21:39.110
Potuz: Oh, Ayton found some Nimbus blocks,

56
00:21:39.720 --> 00:21:45.209
Potuz: But even… even with the same dependent route, 8,000 Nimbus blocks that were attested incorrectly.

57
00:21:49.290 --> 00:21:59.169
Nico Flaig: Yeah, so I previously did some analysis of clients, and it looks like every client just uses the canonical head, or the canonical branch.

58
00:21:59.730 --> 00:22:09.119
Nico Flaig: So, they will not even cast PTC attestations for that branch that you attested to. Because I think it was the Grandinee branch, right?

59
00:22:09.470 --> 00:22:16.190
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Yeah, I believe Teku should, just… Consider the canonical.

60
00:22:17.730 --> 00:22:31.949
Potuz: Well, the problem is that if we are, if we are eventually in a situation in which we're not finalizing, and we have several branches, then if we only send for the canonical branch, we will never achieve quorum on anything.

61
00:22:32.270 --> 00:22:34.460
Potuz: As soon as there's two branches.

62
00:22:34.590 --> 00:22:39.489
Potuz: Then, proposers are going to be free to reorg every payload on every branch.

63
00:22:40.110 --> 00:22:40.790
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Yeah.

64
00:22:40.790 --> 00:22:44.159
Potuz: I think it's a serious liveness risk if we don't…

65
00:22:44.310 --> 00:22:51.060
Potuz: I think we should do an honest attempt to send every attestation, even if it's not on our branch.

66
00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:56.550
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Yeah, I believe… Any, any…

67
00:22:58.150 --> 00:23:06.110
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): low participation branch could… can easily have nothing on… No PTC.

68
00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:08.280
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): So it will be killed.

69
00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:12.509
Potuz: Yeah, that won't be a problem. The problem is if we have a split.

70
00:23:12.810 --> 00:23:13.460
Potuz: If we have.

71
00:23:13.460 --> 00:23:14.080
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Yeah, yeah, I mean…

72
00:23:14.080 --> 00:23:32.510
Potuz: And then, this is kind of easy to do for a powerful agent, create a split for little time, and then we have this proposal boost to try to prevent it, but then, even without proposal boost, if we have no PTC on either side, you can just maintain the branches without any payload.

73
00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:56.530
Nico Flaig: Yeah, so the one thing you mentioned, if we want to do PTC duties per branch, I think this is really difficult. I think this… we never did this, where, like, you do duties on a non-canonical branch, because we always, have the head reorg, and then we track the dependent route, right?

74
00:23:56.860 --> 00:23:58.970
Nico Flaig: So we… we never did this before.

75
00:23:58.970 --> 00:24:09.980
Potuz: Yeah, I think it's… I briefly looked yesterday to try to implement it as a fix for this, and I figured, no, this is going to be a nightmare, so I just sent the lazy one. I'll study if it's too difficult to do, but…

76
00:24:10.220 --> 00:24:11.820
Potuz: It's something to keep in mind.

77
00:24:13.690 --> 00:24:22.440
Nico Flaig: Yeah, there was one idea, so the problem, right, is that we have this absolute number on the PTC where you need to cross the 256 threshold, right?

78
00:24:23.970 --> 00:24:31.840
Potuz: Yeah, but if you want to do it relative to the number of voters, that's even worse. We considered this early on, but that's… that doesn't work even worse.

79
00:24:32.290 --> 00:24:49.420
Nico Flaig: Also, there's another idea which, came in proposed yesterday when we had some random discussion, which is, you basically use your local view, so if you saw the payload timely and available, you will always, vote for that, or pick that.

80
00:24:49.640 --> 00:24:59.029
Nico Flaig: and not listen to the PTC, so you don't need the threshold, and only if the PTC has a maturity against that payload, then you will change your view.

81
00:24:59.440 --> 00:25:03.110
Nico Flaig: So you don't rely on this, or you don't have this problem, right?

82
00:25:07.080 --> 00:25:24.020
Potuz: I… I think this fails, it's too early for me to check, but I think… so we decided not to have attesters, making the decision on the payload, but the proposer, and then the attesters following the proposer, because otherwise, I think this would fail this, the security for the…

83
00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:31.009
Potuz: This would allow, like, late builders, for example, to collude and try to do an ex ante reorg.

84
00:25:31.470 --> 00:25:48.609
Potuz: I mean, if you're going to vote for full because of your view, then you're not going to permit… it's going to make it harder for the next proposer to reorg a payload when he should have reorged a payload, and I think you just make ex ante reorgs easier this way, by a collusion between the builder, so…

85
00:25:48.820 --> 00:25:49.500
Potuz: Yeah.

86
00:25:50.790 --> 00:25:58.789
Nico Flaig: Yeah, I'm just wondering if you have the safeguard when you have the majority of the PTC saying it was not timely that you…

87
00:25:59.140 --> 00:26:00.910
Nico Flaig: would trust the PTC.

88
00:26:01.790 --> 00:26:13.970
Potuz: Yeah, but the problem with this is that if you hold, like, say, 2% and you create a split for 49% of the PTC saying something, then you can prevent always the majority of the PTC to achieve anything.

89
00:26:14.300 --> 00:26:18.330
Potuz: We'd only… With only 50%, with only 2% of your stake.

90
00:26:23.050 --> 00:26:28.089
Nico Flaig: So is that the issue you also described, or… there was, like, an issue you opened, I think.

91
00:26:28.090 --> 00:26:30.629
Potuz: Yeah, yeah, so it's similar to that.

92
00:26:32.570 --> 00:26:36.810
Nico Flaig: Okay, yeah, I think I haven't thought enough about that to give you an answer, but…

93
00:26:38.130 --> 00:26:45.870
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): So, is this a general problem of small committees? So, whenever we decide to…

94
00:26:45.990 --> 00:26:53.640
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): address anything in the chain. With small committees, we end up in this possible situation, correct?

95
00:26:53.640 --> 00:27:12.949
Potuz: I mean, it's… the general problem is that we need to deal with a situation in which a malicious actor can create an arbitrary split, but we are under the assumption that the smaller committees are chosen in a uniform manner, randomly, from the whole committee.

96
00:27:12.970 --> 00:27:24.550
Potuz: So, we are under the assumption that whatever split this malicious actor creates is the same split on the attester's side and on the PTC side.

97
00:27:24.890 --> 00:27:37.370
Potuz: So the issue that I raised, I think it wasn't so… so dangerous, because it would create a different split on the PTC, which is a small committee, and the large committee. But I think for what Nico is describing, this is not necessarily the case.

98
00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:54.290
Nico Flaig: But also, don't we have this already? So if the… if the tester didn't see the payload timely, but the PTC majority says it's timely, we'll go with the PTC, right?

99
00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:57.839
Potuz: Yes, correct.

100
00:28:01.180 --> 00:28:05.590
Nico Flaig: So, and why does this not suffer the same issue as the other way around?

101
00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:15.030
Potuz: Well, because the… you follow the proposer, so what the attesters do is they follow the proposer, they don't follow whatever the PTC says.

102
00:28:15.360 --> 00:28:21.330
Potuz: They follow the proposal, and the PTC is there just to allow the proposer to be able to decide on reorging.

103
00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:28.249
Nico Flaig: Yeah, but with the current spec, the proposal also follows the PTC, right?

104
00:28:29.110 --> 00:28:38.919
Potuz: Not really. So the proposal follows the PTC only in the case where there's a majority that says it wasn't timely.

105
00:28:40.440 --> 00:28:45.200
Nico Flaig: Oh, exactly, but that's the case I want to have as attesters as well, basically.

106
00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:51.769
Potuz: Yeah, and I claim that making the attesters, make the decision instead of the proposer.

107
00:28:52.120 --> 00:28:55.789
Potuz: Comes with a bunch of ex-ante reorgs that become easier.

108
00:28:56.230 --> 00:29:04.650
Potuz: then this was the reason why Francesco wanted… was against having this just in poor choice. We could have just put this in should extend payload.

109
00:29:05.120 --> 00:29:14.819
Potuz: And that would force attesters, instead of, like, this new should build on full. And the reason was because we don't want attesters to make the decision.

110
00:29:15.810 --> 00:29:18.140
Potuz: It also has some liveness issues, too.

111
00:29:33.530 --> 00:29:39.599
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, so the fix will be launched on the DevNet soonish, or what's the…

112
00:29:39.600 --> 00:29:47.910
Potuz: It should be already building, but I'm not sure if, I'm not sure if we're gonna be able to catch up to head, though. If we catch up to head, it should be fine.

113
00:29:51.280 --> 00:29:54.299
Parithosh Jayanthi: Oh, nice. Wait, why wouldn't it catch up to head?

114
00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:54.780
Potuz: Well.

115
00:29:54.780 --> 00:29:56.210
Barnabas: It's rolling now.

116
00:29:56.210 --> 00:30:02.010
Potuz: Everyone was having trouble set… everyone was having trouble sending, range…

117
00:30:02.120 --> 00:30:04.809
Potuz: Range payloads and range blocks, so…

118
00:30:04.810 --> 00:30:06.020
Parithosh Jayanthi: Yeah.

119
00:30:06.020 --> 00:30:08.739
Potuz: We start down low, but downscoring everyone again.

120
00:30:10.810 --> 00:30:18.080
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): By the way, did you double-check that it's not your bag, and it's actually… Pints…

121
00:30:18.840 --> 00:30:24.029
Potuz: No, I haven't. So last… so we do have, one bug in which

122
00:30:24.390 --> 00:30:38.259
Potuz: So, I'm sure clients are sending something incorrect, because we do log. There is an… there is an inconsistent, there's an inconsistent payload and block. So, this one, we're sure. Some clients are sending inconsistent

123
00:30:38.370 --> 00:30:39.980
Potuz: Payload and blocks.

124
00:30:40.290 --> 00:30:46.170
Potuz: But the problem is that, we are downscoring the… we were downscoring the wrong peer.

125
00:30:48.040 --> 00:30:48.610
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Okay.

126
00:30:54.470 --> 00:31:06.759
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, so plan A is gonna be, yeah, recovering DevNet 5. Let's hope that works out. Nico, do you maybe want to briefly talk about, Death Star and what it's doing, and…

127
00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:10.130
Parithosh Jayanthi: Maybe what types of bugs we should be focusing on?

128
00:31:11.350 --> 00:31:17.300
Nico Flaig: So the current behavior is really simple, so it just builds on empty, basically.

129
00:31:17.580 --> 00:31:28.969
Nico Flaig: So even if the payload is timely, it just tries to build on empty, and then the… what we should, like, ideally, what should happen is that block should always be orphaned.

130
00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:36.419
Nico Flaig: But, there were some cases where Grandinee and Nimbus together still voted for the block, and then I think…

131
00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:48.549
Nico Flaig: So I… I think, put us, we concluded that, so with… there was, like, a threshold, and then if the Death Star block gets proposal boost, it, like, barely crosses the threshold to become head.

132
00:31:48.890 --> 00:31:52.739
Nico Flaig: I think that was the observation, because we had also, like, roughly…

133
00:31:52.910 --> 00:31:57.510
Nico Flaig: 20% of attesters voting for it, wrongly.

134
00:31:58.290 --> 00:32:01.679
Nico Flaig: So yeah, so that's basically what it does right now.

135
00:32:05.030 --> 00:32:11.029
Parithosh Jayanthi: Nice, very cool. So, once the fork choice bugs are fixed, Tekunically, everyone should be able to handle this.

136
00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:15.349
Nico Flaig: Yeah, DevStar block should never be part of the canonical chain.

137
00:32:16.300 --> 00:32:17.380
Parithosh Jayanthi: Makes sense.

138
00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:30.240
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): During my testing, I also had my own Teku, AvilTecho, building late beacon blocks and late… and publishing late payload.

139
00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:36.809
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): I was thinking if this could be… I can… I can provide,

140
00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:39.560
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): An image with the additional

141
00:32:40.220 --> 00:32:48.239
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Parameters to… to maybe include this in the… in the… in the network if we want to do additional tests.

142
00:32:51.110 --> 00:32:52.599
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): The test for choice.

143
00:32:56.280 --> 00:32:58.610
Parithosh Jayanthi: Yeah, that would be nice. Thank you.

144
00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:13.269
Parithosh Jayanthi: Cool. Okay, next item, is it worth discussing DevNet's plans, or should we just for now, focus on DevNet 5? We take it on ACDT on Monday?

145
00:33:20.570 --> 00:33:24.369
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, I'll take it as focus on DevNet 5 for now.

146
00:33:25.680 --> 00:33:34.459
Parithosh Jayanthi: Let's move on to Glamsterdam. The first topic, on the agenda is from James.

147
00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:38.710
Parithosh Jayanthi: Do you want to introduce it? Gloas Proposer Preference EIPs?

148
00:33:40.080 --> 00:33:53.050
James He: Sure. Well, this is the Gloas, Proposer Preference APIs, PR for the Beacon API.

149
00:33:53.200 --> 00:34:04.010
James He: So this PR, introduces the, two endpoints, the POST and the GET for proposer preferences.

150
00:34:04.310 --> 00:34:22.260
James He: It also adds the, server-side event for proposer preferences, and it deprecates the, prepare beacon proposer and, register validator endpoints.

151
00:34:22.810 --> 00:34:33.649
James He: One caveat is with the deprecation of the prepare beacon Proposer endpoint. I added to the description of…

152
00:34:34.050 --> 00:34:42.480
James He: Beacon Committee subscriptions, that, that endpoint will be used to track

153
00:34:42.610 --> 00:34:52.970
James He: what local validators are connected to that particular beacon node. Right now, Prysm is using Prepare Beacon

154
00:34:53.090 --> 00:34:56.269
James He: Proposer's endpoint to do that tracking?

155
00:34:56.690 --> 00:35:08.139
James He: But, this is recommending we switch to the Beacon Committee subscriptions endpoint, after this change.

156
00:35:09.040 --> 00:35:14.430
James He: So I just wanted to raise this, if there's any…

157
00:35:14.750 --> 00:35:19.970
James He: any more concerns. I think all the comments were addressed.

158
00:35:20.490 --> 00:35:23.690
James He: So, just wanted to move that along.

159
00:35:28.550 --> 00:35:31.860
Parithosh Jayanthi: Nice. Are there any objections to this change?

160
00:35:38.550 --> 00:35:42.080
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, cool. Then I'll leave it to the maintainers to merge it in.

161
00:35:43.370 --> 00:35:52.519
Parithosh Jayanthi: The next one we have is from… I wanna say, Cayman?

162
00:35:52.850 --> 00:35:59.600
Parithosh Jayanthi: Yeah, it's from Cayman, about mandatory quick as primary transport. Is Cayman here?

163
00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:03.039
Parithosh Jayanthi: Or can someone speak on our behalf?

164
00:36:09.180 --> 00:36:19.239
Matthew Keil: Yeah, so, feels like Quick is kind of the default, in many, many clients today, even though,

165
00:36:19.630 --> 00:36:22.510
Matthew Keil: We specify,

166
00:36:22.730 --> 00:36:31.310
Matthew Keil: The standard, transport, and so we're proposing to make quick the default with the fallback.

167
00:36:31.550 --> 00:36:36.760
Matthew Keil: So not really breaking change, but just a step towards,

168
00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:41.189
Matthew Keil: towards QUIC as a… as the… as the default transport.

