01:23:31.730 --> 01:23:51.330
Raúl Kripalani: owning or kind of, like, sharing a pool of validators, but most importantly, all of those validators are usually sitting behind a single, beacon chain view. So, Tekunically, they were testing at once. They were testing, like, one entity, right? Because they have kind of, like, this one source of truth. So the gist of this proposal is…

555
01:23:51.340 --> 01:23:56.569
Raúl Kripalani: We found a way to make it so that we could

556
01:23:56.780 --> 01:24:03.099
Raúl Kripalani: Aggregate that we could allow these operators to collect the attestations of

557
01:24:03.160 --> 01:24:21.820
Raúl Kripalani: the validators that are co-scheduled on the same committee, on the same slot, same point in time, and just send a single pre-aggregated, message on the wire. Currently, with the stats that I've collected from Beacon Chain, this is…

558
01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:30.119
Raúl Kripalani: the current distribution of the top 10 largest entities by the share validator set. These further decompose into sub-entities, so…

559
01:24:30.120 --> 01:24:48.119
Raúl Kripalani: There's… there's some give and take in… when… when calculating what the consolidation factor, could be, and this is precisely the simulation that I'm preparing, because I think it's going to be useful for us to evaluate this together. But we are ex… with this, if every validate… if every entity

