01:25:43.620 --> 01:26:06.700
Raúl Kripalani: slot, then this is all of the unique data that we're collecting. Sukun presented some of the proposals that, from the networking team, we had been developing around better wire efficiency for this. There's some normalization that can be done. There's a lot that we can already squeeze out of this, and this proposal adds onto what we can squeeze.

565
01:26:06.740 --> 01:26:14.160
Raúl Kripalani: So just to kind of, like, give you a broad stroke, this goes into a lot of detail, so I'm just gonna go…

566
01:26:14.450 --> 01:26:22.790
Raúl Kripalani: I'm just gonna kind of, like, voice over some of the key elements of this proposal. The whole…

567
01:26:22.920 --> 01:26:28.249
Raúl Kripalani: Idea, or, like, the main notion is that, there is…

568
01:26:28.260 --> 01:26:45.339
Raúl Kripalani: within… so, say, for example, you've got a operator that has, for example, 20 validators that are scheduled on the same committee, on the same slot. Those 20 validators could, together, just emit a single, pre-aggregated, attestation.

569
01:26:45.340 --> 01:26:59.899
Raúl Kripalani: And the way they do that is by selecting one validator from those that is going to act as a batcher. And this selection can be done ahead of time, and it can be orchestrated by the… by the beacon client,

570
01:26:59.900 --> 01:27:06.999
Raúl Kripalani: as soon as the validator schedule is known. Every validator will then…

571
01:27:07.060 --> 01:27:15.000
Raúl Kripalani: create what we are calling in this proposal, a batch seal, and it's basically a signature Authorizing that batcher.

572
01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:33.059
Raúl Kripalani: to include their attestation in the batch or the pre-aggregate. So this is kind of like a commitment of saying, hey, or more… more of a consent for a validator to say, hey, this other validator that is a peer of mine in this set, is…

573
01:27:33.210 --> 01:27:37.499
Raúl Kripalani: authorized to send an aggregate. That includes me.

574
01:27:37.770 --> 01:27:50.499
Raúl Kripalani: And then, when the slot arrives, the validators are gonna emit their single attestations, and they're gonna collect them internally, within the Beacon… the Beacon client is gonna… is gonna collect them.

575
01:27:50.500 --> 01:27:58.710
Raúl Kripalani: It's gonna form the aggregate, and then it's gonna send that aggregate to the batcher for it to sign over the entire batch.

576
01:27:58.910 --> 01:28:03.079
Raúl Kripalani: The data structures look like this.

577
01:28:03.360 --> 01:28:06.459
Raúl Kripalani: there is no SSZ

578
01:28:06.850 --> 01:28:22.280
Raúl Kripalani: involvement here. There is no changes to SSZ, there is no changes to slashing, there is no change to on-chain data structures. What you're seeing here is just network data structures. The… what lands on-chain is just the attestation as we know it today.

579
01:28:22.390 --> 01:28:24.070
Raúl Kripalani: So…

580
01:28:24.210 --> 01:28:34.799
Raúl Kripalani: just to kind of, like, represent this on the wire, we call the single attestation, and we have the batch attestation. The batch attestation is the pre-aggregate.

581
01:28:35.430 --> 01:28:45.260
Raúl Kripalani: And it contains everything the single attestation does, plus these three fields. So it identifies the batcher by validator index within the committee.

582
01:28:45.380 --> 01:28:55.539
Raúl Kripalani: So this is… this is the member of the committee, of course. It then includes the BLS aggregate of all the seals.

583
01:28:55.800 --> 01:29:09.010
Raúl Kripalani: So, this is basically the aggregate that confirms that this batcher is authorized by all of the validators that are participating in this batch to send a batch on their behalf.

584
01:29:09.230 --> 01:29:15.989
Raúl Kripalani: And then it includes its own signature on top of this, sealing… sealing over the entire batch.

585
01:29:16.270 --> 01:29:27.599
Raúl Kripalani: That's basically it. What you see on the left are just pre-images, these are not… this is not data that circulates on the wire, it's just a pre-image that goes on the… that goes into the signing function.

586
01:29:27.720 --> 01:29:40.470
Raúl Kripalani: The validator rules are actually very simple. This is, a little bit more… presents them a little bit more complex, because it kind of, like, unbundles the existing validator rules. But basically.

587
01:29:40.850 --> 01:29:50.110
Raúl Kripalani: what happens is… it hinges on a few principles. First, every validator can participate individually.

588
01:29:50.630 --> 01:30:09.340
Raúl Kripalani: and as a batcher, only once as each role. So that means that if we have 435 attestations, in a particular committee, then the maximum, if everybody happened to be a malicious validator, and everybody emitted, and, you know, there was…

589
01:30:09.580 --> 01:30:10.780
Raúl Kripalani: there was…

590
01:30:11.170 --> 01:30:28.100
Raúl Kripalani: like, the worst case scenario where a single operator owns all of the validators in a particular… in a committee, if that… if that materializes and they act maliciously, the max we could see is 870 attestations. So…

591
01:30:28.500 --> 01:30:35.710
Raúl Kripalani: Because every validator can participate individually by sending a single attestation, but also can participate in a batch.

592
01:30:36.040 --> 01:30:40.540
Raúl Kripalani: Now, this means that spam is completely capped, and this is…

593
01:30:40.700 --> 01:30:51.970
Raúl Kripalani: a really good thing to have. The other alternative solutions that were even stricter and more aggressive in capping potential spam in…

594
01:30:52.430 --> 01:31:00.920
Raúl Kripalani: how does introducing changes to… how does introducing slashing conditions, and so on. So, I think this is a really good trade-off space to be.

595
01:31:01.130 --> 01:31:09.429
Raúl Kripalani: And… so that is kind of, like, one… one of the key validation rules. The second validation rule is that

596
01:31:09.720 --> 01:31:11.340
Raúl Kripalani: a attestation.

597
01:31:11.830 --> 01:31:18.670
Raúl Kripalani: Bit can only… You will drop attestations circulating on the wire.

598
01:31:18.780 --> 01:31:23.170
Raúl Kripalani: If you've already seen that attestation bid included.

599
01:31:23.440 --> 01:31:26.069
Raúl Kripalani: in… in a previous attestation. So this…

